WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.400
Welcome everyone, and in my talk I will discuss some aspects of Shiny Open Source, but before

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:19.400
we move on, let me briefly remind you why our community praises Shiny so much.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:25.719
First of all, you can prototype your applications very fast, so you can create your first POC

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:28.879
in a matter of hours rather than days.

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:34.599
That all comes wrapped in a neat user interface powered by Bootstrap, so you don't really

00:00:34.599 --> 00:00:37.040
need to reinvent the wheel when it comes to styling.

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:41.840
Obviously, you can customize it as it was shown in the previous presentations.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.880
Shiny leverages the power of R when it comes to the data analysis, so in the backend you

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:54.680
can use those powerful packages from the Tidyverse family, for instance, and Shiny also is nicely

00:00:54.720 --> 00:01:00.480
integrated with a large number of visualization packages like ggplot, leaflet, datatable, and

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:05.919
even more. Interactivity, so how different UI components talk to each other is quite

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:11.639
easy to understand, but with all those advantages in mind, sometimes I have the impression that

00:01:11.639 --> 00:01:16.120
we forget that the true power of Shiny lies in the fact that this is fully open source

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:23.519
software, and I came to realize that recently when I was reading again through a blog post

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:30.839
describing the winning solutions to the second annual Shiny contest, and I realized how many

00:01:30.839 --> 00:01:33.839
different applications you can actually use Shiny.

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:41.120
So here we have an interactive data storytelling, we have a machine learning-backed application

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:48.040
for visualizing your musical taste, we have data analysis dashboard that presents the

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:54.040
most popular GitHub repositories, and finally, you can even make games as proven by our very

00:01:54.040 --> 00:02:00.320
own Pedro. But all of that wouldn't be really possible without all of those Shiny

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:06.680
extensions that are available now, and every year there's even more and more of them.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:12.559
So there is no way that I could cover all of them in detail during my 10-minute slot,

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:19.119
but I decided to cherry pick just a few, without which I can't even start thinking about

00:02:19.119 --> 00:02:22.520
starting developing my own Shiny applications.

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:30.520
So let's kick off with ShinyJS, which is a package from Dean Attali that lets you perform

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:35.520
common, useful JavaScript operations in Shiny, like hiding elements, disabling inputs,

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:41.679
resetting values, or alerting some variables that I often use for debugging myself.

00:02:41.679 --> 00:02:46.119
The cool thing, though, is that you don't really need to know any JavaScript to start using

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:51.320
that, because everything is wrapped in R functions that are nicely documented, so it's

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:53.639
quite easy to get started.

00:02:53.639 --> 00:03:01.279
Then we have Shiny Widgets, which is basically a collection of extra components to enhance

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:02.839
your Shiny applications.

00:03:02.839 --> 00:03:07.440
The repository contains a big selection of the components that are usually nicely

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:13.160
documented with little code snippets, such that you can copy and paste the code and adjust it

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:14.479
for your own needs.

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:20.399
Some of my favorite elements are, for example, picker input, those fancy checkbox button,

00:03:20.399 --> 00:03:24.679
or horizontal multiple choice selector.

00:03:24.679 --> 00:03:31.839
Then we have small but rather powerful package, Shiny CSS Loaders, that helps you with

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:36.199
adding loading animations to the output instead of greening them up.

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:43.320
So I mentioned to you already that Shiny uses this power of R for data analysis, but

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:49.639
certain actions can take a while, so it's better to provide our user with some feedback that

00:03:49.639 --> 00:03:52.039
there's something happening in the background.

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:59.440
So you can do it with a simple one-function call with Spinner that adds to your Shiny

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:02.240
those little animations.

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:07.919
OK, and I wouldn't be myself if I haven't mentioned about some packages that help you style

00:04:07.919 --> 00:04:12.360
your apps. As in Appsilon, we care a lot about how the apps look.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:20.279
So starting from the left, we have BS4Dash that provides you with bootstrap for admin LTE

00:04:20.279 --> 00:04:22.160
skin for your dashboards.

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:28.959
Then we have Shiny Mobile that helps you create mobile-ready Shiny apps that look almost

00:04:28.959 --> 00:04:31.720
like native apps for iOS and Android.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:36.559
And then on the right, we have our own Shiny Semantic that helps you to attach an

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:40.839
alternative look to your Shiny applications.

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:47.600
OK, and I mentioned that I just scratched the surface here, so there is even more fantastic

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:52.880
Shiny extensions that you can find on this Shiny Awesome repository that I discovered

00:04:52.880 --> 00:05:03.119
recently. And this little repository summarizes and categorizes various Shiny extensions

00:05:03.119 --> 00:05:07.320
such that you can always find something that you need there.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.160
I encourage you to check it out.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:15.920
OK, but using all those Shiny extensions is just like one way how you can take advantage of

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:23.799
Shiny open sourceness, but you can help yourself with building those tools.

00:05:23.799 --> 00:05:30.839
So first of all, you can start from something as simple as reporting a bug or bringing some

00:05:30.839 --> 00:05:38.359
new idea to the table by creating a new issue on GitHub repository or emailing an author

00:05:38.359 --> 00:05:43.799
of the code. But remember to be respectful with that, as very often open source code is

00:05:43.799 --> 00:05:49.279
created by enthusiasts, or as in our case, this is something that we do outside of our

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:51.559
daily work with clients.

00:05:51.559 --> 00:05:59.920
Then, if you feel comfortable enough actually to fix some bug or contribute with a new

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:05.760
idea to a certain package, feel free to do some coding and create a new pull request.

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:11.040
But remember first about reading and contributing guidelines, as they usually contain

00:06:11.079 --> 00:06:16.480
useful information with what to do or not to do on a given repository.

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:22.640
Remember about testing all of your changes so that you see that you didn't break all the

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:27.160
previous functionalities of the code and always ask politely for a review.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:33.200
It's good to have another pair of eyes to check the quality of your code.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:42.600
OK, but now if you still see that there is no solution to your problem available, then

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:46.399
you can move on and think about creating your own package.

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:50.679
And remember that for starters, it doesn't really need to be perfect.

00:06:50.679 --> 00:06:54.359
Some solution is better than no solution whatsoever.

00:06:54.359 --> 00:07:00.079
And always you may find someone in the community who would be interested in collaborating and

00:07:00.079 --> 00:07:04.839
moving the project forward if you don't really have time to do all the coding on your own.

00:07:04.839 --> 00:07:08.519
And then a couple of tips from me.

00:07:08.519 --> 00:07:14.679
Remember about adding tests to your package from the early beginning, as it will really spare you

00:07:14.679 --> 00:07:18.760
so much troubles at the later stage of the development.

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:21.399
Remember about documenting your code.

00:07:21.399 --> 00:07:25.799
For you, it might be quite obvious how to use your own functions, but not necessarily for the

00:07:25.799 --> 00:07:27.519
users of your package.

00:07:27.519 --> 00:07:35.480
And recently, it became a good practice to add interactive examples to your repository such that

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:42.839
users can test what this package actually can help them with before they even download it.

00:07:42.839 --> 00:07:44.160
And then comes the fun part.

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:49.600
So remember about publishing it, sharing with others to get credits and acknowledgements.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:52.480
It's a really satisfying feeling.

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:59.079
OK, with that, let me mention our very own Appsilon open source family related to Shiny.

00:07:59.079 --> 00:08:05.679
So you have a variety of packages here related to styling, packages that help you with debugging,

00:08:05.679 --> 00:08:08.519
translations and routing.

00:08:08.519 --> 00:08:16.279
I will not go into too much detail here, as we have a separate pre-recorded video available where I

00:08:16.279 --> 00:08:22.119
discuss some of the possibilities of those packages and a little bit more details.

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:27.079
Just let me mention here that every year we try to extend this list.

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:34.960
So stay tuned as later on, Filip and Marek will tell you a little bit more about our two new projects.

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:42.880
OK, so to sort of like prove to you that our packages can be useful, a couple of months ago,

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:52.840
we decided to challenge ourselves and try to implement a fully functional Shiny applications in less than 24 hours.

00:08:52.840 --> 00:09:03.119
So here you have a screenshot from two out of like six entries to this little competition for the comprehensive list of all the amazing solutions.

00:09:03.119 --> 00:09:06.880
You can check our blog post.

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:17.919
And if you can wait and you still want to see all of our packages in action, I encourage you to visit Shiny Tools website that we set up recently.

00:09:17.919 --> 00:09:26.919
And it contains references to the GitHub, to the documentation and live examples of all our packages.

00:09:26.919 --> 00:09:33.119
So we can test them if they can be useful for your Shiny development.

00:09:33.119 --> 00:09:36.799
OK, so that's all I get. Thank you very much for your attention.

00:09:36.799 --> 00:09:42.880
Feel free to ping me if you have any questions and I hope you will enjoy the rest of the session. Cheers.

